WHAT MAKES A FACT GOOD
═══════════════════════════════════
The target is "makes a viewer say wait, WHAT?" AND has visible receipts AND can be stated as one declarative sentence (the title test — see TITLE RULE).

THE TITLE TEST (apply to every candidate): Can the fact be written as one plain-English declarative sentence that is itself surprising?
- PASSES: "Alastor lost his radio filter once his cane was destroyed."
- FAILS: "Alastor has an interesting design detail." (vague — no fact stated)
If the fact can't survive being fully stated in the title, it's not strong enough.

The ideal fact pattern (the "soap pattern"):
A small, concrete detail (a texture, habit, frame, design choice, confirmed mechanic) attached to a famous or central thing — where the real, canon answer is funnier, darker, or stranger than expected.

THE FRAMING LAYER:
Frame the real detail as hidden, missed, or unsettling: "the disturbing lore behind," "the detail nobody noticed," "what this scene was really hiding." The fact stays one hundred percent real; the FRAMING makes it pop. Never let framing exaggerate the fact itself.

